} So, when x is less than or equal to i, what condition must be met to set a[i+1] to 1? Let's think. Suppose x is the length written to the right of a segment. Then, the segment would consist of x elements, followed by the length x. So, the start of the segment would be at position i - x (because the length is at position i). The elements are from i - x to i -1, and the length is at i. So, the start position s would be i - x. But for this to be possible, the code must have previously reached position s. So, the condition would check if a[s] is true (i.e., whether we can start a new segment at s).

Therefore, the code should check if a[i -x] is true. Then, set a[i+1] to 1. So the TODO line's condition would be: a[i - x] 

Because if a[i - x] is 1, then it's possible to start a segment there, which would take x elements (positions i -x to i-1) followed by x (the length at i), thus moving to i+1. Then, the second condition:

if (a[i] && i + x < n)

   a[i+x+1] = 1;

Here, if the current position is reachable (a[i] is true), and adding x to i doesn't exceed n, then mark a[i + x + 1] as reachable. This is probably the case when the current x is the length written to the left of a segment. So, the segment would be x followed by x elements. So, the length is at position i, followed by x elements (positions i+1 to i+x). Then, the next position after this segment would be i + x + 1.
